        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          'Assists' is a tricky stat to use accurately. It's dependant on the player putting the ball in the back of the net from your pass. Oezil's first today was a 'lucky' assist I agree, but these things even out over the season (meaning he will lay one on a plate in the box which somebody will miss). I use "chances created" as a better indicator. In that regard, Oezil has the most of anyone in the top 4 European leagues this season with 67, Neymar is 2nd with 52 and the whole bottom half of that league acts as stat fodder for the top players. Just thought I'd share.

        • [ - ] The_Analyst - member since 23-Jun-14

          @SteveHyland Good to see more people talking about this. I understand assists are a tricky stat to measure. If Claudio Bravo passes the ball all across the field to Messi, and in the space of 5 seconds, Messi takes on two players and scored, was Bravo really the generator of that goal? Maybe for some, not for me. I don't work in these stats sites to come up with a more accurate way to inform us of the production of a player, but using the criteria of "who gave the last pass" as an assist is rather lazy. I agree that chances created is a more precise indicator for individual performances. Such as "goal opportunities" are more accurate than "shots on target" when it comes to teams. Well...I guess in the end of the day football is about quality and improvisation, not mathematical algorithms.

Using chances created, the best providers always finish in the top range so it's a valid stat to compare providing you use caveats such as position and formation. The best players, the ones who set up chances with the spin and weight as you say, always end up creating the most because if you have the touch to be able to lay it so easily on a plate, you also have the ability to create where others can't. Silva, Cazorla, Rakitic to name 3 others.

          This comment is not about Ozil's quality (which shouldn't be in discussion) but about how we measure assists. I get why the first goal was considered an assist, but should it? Ozil just passed the ball to Walcott to keep the attack flowing. You can even argue he wanted to pass the ball to Monreal. Walcott then received the ball and scored a great goal out of nowhere. However there's a clear difference with the second goal, in which Ozil assisted Giroud perfectly, who didn't even need to control the ball since the pass was perfect. I'm just saying that giving assists to the player who did the last pass before the goal, seems like a lazy approach if they didn't heavily contribute to the goal.

        • [ - ] TacticalMastermind - member since 16-Sep-14

          @The_Analyst It is to reward unselfish play. Encourage team work. It would be just as wrong to not credit an assist for playing a simple pass and it would be to not give a player the goal for scoring into an empty net. In reality it is technically an assist and technically the goal of the player scoring a tap in. You could say it's unfair to count penalties against a players' stats, that it should go to the winner of the penalty or even just to the team. Basic examples, I don't want to go into much detail as the debate will last forever and never end up at a conclusion with everyone satisfied.
